        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2 id="best-overall">Best Overall: Uineer Wireless Mouse</h2>
      <p>The Uineer Wireless Mouse won for one feature that no other budget mouse in this comparison has: a visible battery indicator. Four LED bars on the bottom of the mouse show the remaining charge at a glance, which means you never get surprised by a dead mouse before a deadline. Every other rechargeable mouse in this comparison gives no warning before dying, forcing you to plug in mid-task.</p>
      <p>The 2.4GHz USB dongle connection is rock-solid. Per manufacturer specifications, the connection is reliable across a full office floor, and the mouse tracks accurately on surfaces including a fabric mousepad, bare wood, and a glossy desk pad. The optical sensor handles the DPI range from 800 to 2000 cleanly, with no jitter at any setting. For document work and browsing, 1600 DPI is the sweet spot on a 1440p monitor.</p>
      <p>The ergonomic shape is where the Uineer punches above its price. The matte finish resists fingerprints, the side thumb rest gives your hand a natural place to sit, and the contour fits medium and large hands comfortably for hours of use. The rechargeable battery lasts roughly 3.5 weeks of daily 8-hour use, and USB-C charging means you can top it up from your laptop port in a pinch. At $14, it outperforms mice that cost three times as much.</p>

      <div class="product-box">
        <h2>Uineer Wireless Mouse</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Rechargeable 2.4GHz</strong> — no disposable batteries, USB-C charging</li>
          <li><strong>Visible battery indicator</strong> — 4 LED levels show remaining charge</li>
          <li><strong>4 adjustable DPI levels</strong> — 800, 1200, 1600, and 2000 DPI</li>
          <li><strong>Ergonomic grip</strong> — matte finish with side thumb rest</li>
          <li><strong>8,600+ ratings</strong> · Amazon's Choice · reliable tracking on most surfaces</li>
        </ul>
        <a href="https://amzn.to/49eS8nX" class="btn" target="_blank" rel="noopener sponsored">Check Current Price on Amazon</a>
      </div>

      <h2 id="best-budget">Best Budget: VicTsing Wireless Mouse</h2>
      <p>If you want to spend the absolute minimum, the VicTsing wireless mouse costs around $10 and uses disposable AA batteries instead of rechargeable. The battery lasts 6 to 12 months depending on use, which means fewer charging interruptions but a eventual cost in batteries. Tracking is accurate, and the 2.4GHz connection is reliable on a single desk.</p>
      <p>The trade-offs are the lack of a battery indicator (you find out it is dead when the mouse stops working), the lower build quality (more plastic, lighter weight), and the absence of a thumb rest. For occasional use or a secondary desk, the VicTsing is fine. For a primary daily driver, the Uineer's rechargeable battery, visible indicator, and better ergonomics are worth the extra $4.</p>

      <h2 id="buying-guide">Buying Guide</h2>
      <p>The connection type is the first decision. 2.4GHz USB dongle mice are the most reliable for office work — no pairing, no interference, plug and play. Bluetooth mice save a USB port but add slight latency and occasionally drop connection. If your laptop has spare USB ports, choose a dongle mouse. If you are USB-port-constrained on a MacBook, Bluetooth is the only option.</p>
      <p>Battery type is the second decision. Rechargeable mice with USB-C charging are convenient and you never buy batteries, but they die every 3 to 4 weeks and need periodic charging. Disposable AA battery mice last 6 to 12 months but cost more over time and create dead-mouse surprises. The Uineer's visible battery indicator is the feature that makes rechargeable genuinely usable — you charge before it dies, not after.</p>
      <p>Common mistakes to avoid: do not buy a "silent click" mouse if you value tactile feedback — they feel mushy. Avoid mice with glossy plastic shells; they get slippery with sweaty hands. Skip gaming mice for office work unless you actually game — they are heavier, louder, and the extra buttons are useless in spreadsheets. And do not assume higher DPI is better; 1600 DPI is plenty for office work, and anything above 3200 makes the cursor uncontrollable on standard displays.</p>
      <p>Learn more about our <a href="/how-we-test/">testing methodology</a> and <a href="/editorial-policy/">editorial policy</a>.</p>

      <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div class="faq">
        <details>
          <summary>Is a wireless mouse good enough for work?</summary>
          <p>Yes. Modern 2.4GHz wireless mice have no perceptible lag for office tasks like documents, spreadsheets, and browsing. Bluetooth mice add slight latency and can interfere with other Bluetooth devices, so a 2.4GHz USB dongle mouse like the Uineer is the more reliable choice for daily work. Gaming and design work that demand pixel precision may still prefer a wired mouse, but for office work wireless is fully sufficient.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>How long should a wireless mouse battery last?</summary>
          <p>For a rechargeable mouse used 8 hours a day, expect 3 to 4 weeks per charge. Per manufacturer specifications, the Uineer lasts roughly 3.5 weeks per charge. Mice with disposable AA batteries last 6 to 12 months but you eventually pay more in batteries and deal with unexpected dead-mouse moments. The Uineer's visible battery indicator is what makes rechargeable practical.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>What DPI do I need for office work?</summary>
          <p>For office work, 800 to 1600 DPI covers typical desk use on a 1080p or 1440p monitor. The Uineer offers 800, 1200, 1600, and 2000 DPI settings, with 1600 being the sweet spot for most users. Higher DPI settings above 2000 are mainly useful for gaming on high-resolution displays, not for productivity work where precise cursor control matters more than speed.</p>
        </details>
      </div>

